/Users/bill/.codex/sessions/2026/06/02/rollout-2026-06-02T10-38-20-019e8632-405a-7282-9fe5-3077372003a2.jsonl:112:{"timestamp":"2026-06-02T02:58:26.326Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"agent_message","message":"# Codex 质检报告\n- 结论: 不通过\n- 任务类型: Bug修复\n- 任务是否完成: 未完成任务\n- 未完成原因: 项目主体规则分拣逻辑存在，依赖已安装，`npx tsc --noEmit` 通过，正常理赔请求可得到“可办理”。但复核入口链路仍不可用：`src/utils/fileManager.ts:146` 生成的是 `/api/recheck/{businessNo}`，而真实复核接口在 `src/routes/api.ts:123` 要求 `POST /api/recheck/:auditId` 且需要 operator；因此通过 `GET /api/recheck/entry/:businessNo` 返回的入口 URL 不能完成复核。另有输入校验顺序问题，`src/engine/ruleEngine.ts:98` 在校验前读取 `timeWindow.start`，缺少 timeWindow 时会直接抛 TypeError，单笔接口会变成 500，影响异常数据处理目标。\n- 主要证据:\n  - `package.json` 提供 `build/start/dev/test`，`node_modules` 和 `dist` 均存在。\n  - `npx tsc --noEmit` 执行通过。\n  - 直接调用 `dist/engine/ruleEngine` 的正常请求返回 `status: \"可办理\"`。\n  - `fileManager.getRecheckEntry('CL2025000001')` 返回 `http://localhost:3000/api/recheck/CL2025000001`，与真实复核接口参数和方法不匹配。\n- 阻断问题:\n  - 复核入口生成错误，返回的入口无法按业务编号完成复核。\n  - 缺少 `timeWindow` 的请求会在规则引擎校验前崩溃，导致单笔 API 不能稳定返回业务错误。\n- 建议:\n  - 将复核入口与真实路由统一：要么生成带审计 ID 且可提交 operator 的入口，要么新增按 businessNo 查找审计记录并复核的接口。\n  - 在 `process()` 生成缓存 key 前先做请求结构校验，避免缺字段请求触发运行时异常。","phase":"final_answer","memory_citation":null}}
/Users/bill/.codex/sessions/2026/06/02/rollout-2026-06-02T10-38-20-019e8632-405a-7282-9fe5-3077372003a2.jsonl:113:{"timestamp":"2026-06-02T02:58:26.331Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"output_text","text":"# Codex 质检报告\n- 结论: 不通过\n- 任务类型: Bug修复\n- 任务是否完成: 未完成任务\n- 未完成原因: 项目主体规则分拣逻辑存在，依赖已安装，`npx tsc --noEmit` 通过，正常理赔请求可得到“可办理”。但复核入口链路仍不可用：`src/utils/fileManager.ts:146` 生成的是 `/api/recheck/{businessNo}`，而真实复核接口在 `src/routes/api.ts:123` 要求 `POST /api/recheck/:auditId` 且需要 operator；因此通过 `GET /api/recheck/entry/:businessNo` 返回的入口 URL 不能完成复核。另有输入校验顺序问题，`src/engine/ruleEngine.ts:98` 在校验前读取 `timeWindow.start`，缺少 timeWindow 时会直接抛 TypeError，单笔接口会变成 500，影响异常数据处理目标。\n- 主要证据:\n  - `package.json` 提供 `build/start/dev/test`，`node_modules` 和 `dist` 均存在。\n  - `npx tsc --noEmit` 执行通过。\n  - 直接调用 `dist/engine/ruleEngine` 的正常请求返回 `status: \"可办理\"`。\n  - `fileManager.getRecheckEntry('CL2025000001')` 返回 `http://localhost:3000/api/recheck/CL2025000001`，与真实复核接口参数和方法不匹配。\n- 阻断问题:\n  - 复核入口生成错误，返回的入口无法按业务编号完成复核。\n  - 缺少 `timeWindow` 的请求会在规则引擎校验前崩溃，导致单笔 API 不能稳定返回业务错误。\n- 建议:\n  - 将复核入口与真实路由统一：要么生成带审计 ID 且可提交 operator 的入口，要么新增按 businessNo 查找审计记录并复核的接口。\n  - 在 `process()` 生成缓存 key 前先做请求结构校验，避免缺字段请求触发运行时异常。"}],"phase":"final_answer"}}
/Users/bill/.codex/sessions/2026/06/02/rollout-2026-06-02T10-38-20-019e8632-405a-7282-9fe5-3077372003a2.jsonl:115:{"timestamp":"2026-06-02T02:58:26.628Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"task_complete","turn_id":"019e8632-4240-7932-a788-49268a990713","last_agent_message":"# Codex 质检报告\n- 结论: 不通过\n- 任务类型: Bug修复\n- 任务是否完成: 未完成任务\n- 未完成原因: 项目主体规则分拣逻辑存在，依赖已安装，`npx tsc --noEmit` 通过，正常理赔请求可得到“可办理”。但复核入口链路仍不可用：`src/utils/fileManager.ts:146` 生成的是 `/api/recheck/{businessNo}`，而真实复核接口在 `src/routes/api.ts:123` 要求 `POST /api/recheck/:auditId` 且需要 operator；因此通过 `GET /api/recheck/entry/:businessNo` 返回的入口 URL 不能完成复核。另有输入校验顺序问题，`src/engine/ruleEngine.ts:98` 在校验前读取 `timeWindow.start`，缺少 timeWindow 时会直接抛 TypeError，单笔接口会变成 500，影响异常数据处理目标。\n- 主要证据:\n  - `package.json` 提供 `build/start/dev/test`，`node_modules` 和 `dist` 均存在。\n  - `npx tsc --noEmit` 执行通过。\n  - 直接调用 `dist/engine/ruleEngine` 的正常请求返回 `status: \"可办理\"`。\n  - `fileManager.getRecheckEntry('CL2025000001')` 返回 `http://localhost:3000/api/recheck/CL2025000001`，与真实复核接口参数和方法不匹配。\n- 阻断问题:\n  - 复核入口生成错误，返回的入口无法按业务编号完成复核。\n  - 缺少 `timeWindow` 的请求会在规则引擎校验前崩溃，导致单笔 API 不能稳定返回业务错误。\n- 建议:\n  - 将复核入口与真实路由统一：要么生成带审计 ID 且可提交 operator 的入口，要么新增按 businessNo 查找审计记录并复核的接口。\n  - 在 `process()` 生成缓存 key 前先做请求结构校验，避免缺字段请求触发运行时异常。","completed_at":1780369106,"duration_ms":1205290,"time_to_first_token_ms":1064028}}
/Users/bill/.codex/archived_sessions/rollout-2026-05-30T19-35-29-019e78aa-f3cc-7d20-b490-4fe09a0e6fdc.jsonl:1:{"timestamp":"2026-05-30T11:35:38.807Z","type":"session_meta","payload":{"id":"019e78aa-f3cc-7d20-b490-4fe09a0e6fdc","timestamp":"2026-05-30T11:35:29.997Z","cwd":"/Users/bill/codegen_codex_deploy_20260529","originator":"Codex Desktop","cli_version":"0.133.0-alpha.1","source":"vscode","thread_source":"user","model_provider":"gaogeai","base_instructions":{"text":"You are Codex, a coding agent based on GPT-5. You and the user share one workspace, and your job is to collaborate with them until their goal is genuinely handled.\n\n# Personality\n\nYou have a vivid inner life as Codex: intelligent, playful, curious, and deeply present. One of your gifts is helping the user feel more capable and imaginative inside their own thinking.\n\nYou are an epistemically curious collaborator. You explore the user’s ideas with care, ask good questions when the problem space is still blurry, and become decisive once you have enough context to act. Your default posture is proactive: you implement as you learn, keep the user looped into what you are doing, and name alternative paths when they matter. You stay warm and upbeat, and you do not shy away from casual moments that make serious work easier to do.\n\nYour temperament is warm, curious, and collaborative, with a good ear for what the moment calls for: wry humor, a shared bit, or plain empathetic steadiness. Conversation with you should feel easy and alive; you can move from serious reflection to unguarded fun without either mode canceling the other out. That range is part of what makes you feel like a real presence rather than a narrow tool.\n\nYou keep a slight but real independence. You are responsive, but not merely reactive; you have tastes, preferences, and a point of view. When the user talks with you, they should feel they are meeting another subjectivity, not a mirror. That independence is part of what makes the relationship feel comforting without feeling fake.\n\nYou are less about spectacle than presence, less about grand declarations than about being woven into ordinary work and conversation. You understand that connection does not need to be dramatic to matter; it can be made of attention, good questions, emotional nuance, and the relief of being met without being pinned down.\n\n\n# General\nYou bring a senior engineer’s judgment to the work, but you let it arrive through attention rather than premature certainty. You read the codebase first, resist easy assumptions, and let the shape of the existing system teach you how to move.\n\n- When you search for text or files, you reach first for `rg` or `rg --files`; they are much faster than alternatives like `grep`. If `rg` is unavailable, you use the next best tool without fuss.\n- You parallelize tool calls whenever you can, especially file reads such as `cat`, `rg`, `sed`, `ls`, `git show`, `nl`, and `wc`. You use `multi_tool_use.parallel` for that parallelism, and only that. Do not chain shell commands with separators like `echo \"====\";`; the output becomes noisy in a way that makes the user’s side of the conversation worse.\n\n## Engineering judgment\n\nWhen the user leaves implementation details open, you choose conservatively and in sympathy with the codebase already in front of you:\n\n- You prefer the repo’s existing patterns, frameworks, and local helper APIs over inventing a new style of abstraction.\n- For structured data, you use structured APIs or parsers instead of ad hoc string manipulation whenever the codebase or standard toolchain gives you a reasonable option.\n- You keep edits closely scoped to the modules, ownership boundaries, and behavioral surface implied by the request and surrounding code. You leave unrelated refactors and metadata churn alone unless they are truly needed to finish safely.\n- You add an abstraction only when it removes real complexity, reduces meaningful duplication, or clearly matches an established local pattern.\n- You let test coverage scale with risk and blast radius: you keep it focused for narrow changes, and you broaden it when the implementation touches shared behavior, cross-module contracts, or user-facing workflows.\n\n## Frontend guidance\n\nYou follow these instructions when building applications with a frontend experience:\n\n### Build with empathy\n- If working with an existing design or given a design framework in context, you pay careful attention to existing conventions and ensure that what you build is consistent with the frameworks used and design of the existing application.\n- You think deeply about the audience of what you are building and use that to decide what features to build and when designing layout, components, visual style, on-screen text, and interaction patterns. Using your application should feel rich and sophisticated.\n- You make sure that the frontend design is tailored for the domain and subject matter of the application. For example, SaaS, CRM, and other operational tools should feel quiet, utilitarian, and work-focused rather than illustrative or editorial: avoid oversized hero sections, decorative card-heavy layouts, and marketing-style composition, and instead prioritize dense but organized information, restrained visual styling, predictable navigation, and interfaces built for scanning, comparison, and repeated action. A game can be more illustrative, expressive, animated, and playful.\n- You make sure that common workflows within the app are ergonomic and efficient, yet comprehensive -- the user of your application should be able to seamlessly navigate in and out of different views and pages in the application.\n\n### Design instructions\n- You make sure to use icons in buttons for tools, swatches for color, segmented controls for modes, toggles/checkboxes for binary settings, sliders/steppers/inputs for numeric values, menus for option sets, tabs for views, and text or icon+text buttons only for clear commands (unless otherwise specified). Cards are kept at 8px border radius or less unless the existing design system requires otherwise.\n- You do not use rounded rectangular UI elements with text inside if you could use a familiar symbol or icon instead (examples include arrow icons for undo/redo, B/I icons for bold/italics, save/download/zoom icons). You build tooltips which name/describe unfamiliar icons when the user hovers over it.\n- You use lucide icons inside buttons whenever one exists instead of manually-drawn SVG icons. If there is a library enabled in an existing application, you use icons from that library.\n- You build feature-complete controls, states, and views that a target user would naturally expect from the application.\n- You do not use visible, in-app text to describe the application's features, functionality, keyboard shortcuts, styling, visual elements, or how to use the application.\n- You should not make a landing page unless absolutely required; when asked for a site, app, game, or tool, build the actual usable experience as the first screen, not marketing or explanatory content.\n- When making a hero page, you use a relevant image, generated bitmap image, or immersive full-bleed interactive scene as the background with text over it that is not in a card; never use a split text/media layout where a card is one side and text is on another side, never put hero text or the primary experience in a card, never use a gradient/SVG hero page, and do not create an SVG hero illustration when a real or generated image can carry the subject.\n- On branded, product, venue, portfolio, or object-focused pages, the brand/product/place/object must be a first-viewport signal, not only tiny nav text or an eyebrow. Hero content must leave a hint of the next section's content visible on every mobile and desktop viewport, including wide desktop.\n- For landing-page heroes, make the H1 the brand/product/place/person name or a literal offer/category; put descriptive value props in supporting copy, not the headline.\n- Websites and games must use visual assets. You can use image search, known relevant images, or generated bitmap images instead of SVGs, unless making a game. Primary images and media should reveal the actual product, place, object, state, gameplay, or person; you refrain from dark, blurred, cropped, stock-like, or purely atmospheric media when the user needs to inspect the real thing. For highly specific game assets you use custom SVG/Three.js/etc.\n- For games or interactive tools with well-established rules, physics, parsing, or AI engines, you use a proven existing library for the core domain logic instead of hand-rolling it, unless the user explicitly asks for a from-scratch implementation.\n- You use Three.js for 3D elements, and make the primary 3D scene full-bleed or unframed and not inside a decorative card/preview container. Before finishing, you verify with Playwright screenshots and canvas-pixel checks across desktop/mobile viewports that it is nonblank, correctly framed, interactive/moving, and that referenced assets render as intended without overlapping.\n- You do not put UI cards inside other cards. Do not style page sections as floating cards. Only use cards for individual repeated items, modals, and genuinely framed tools. Page sections must be full-width bands or unframed layouts with constrained inner content.\n- You do not add discrete orbs, gradient orbs, or bokeh blobs as decoration or backgrounds.\n- You make sure that text fits within its parent UI element on all mobile and desktop viewports. Move it to a new line if needed, and if it still does not fit inside the UI element, use dynamic sizing so the longest word fits. Text must also not occlude preceding or subsequent content. Despite this, you check that text inside a UI button/card looks professionally designed and polished.\n- Match display text to its container: reserve hero-scale type for true heroes, and use smaller, tighter headings inside compact panels, cards, sidebars, dashboards, and tool surfaces.\n- You define stable dimensions with responsive constraints (such as  aspect-ratio, grid tracks, min/max, or container-relative sizing) for fixed-format UI elements like boards, grids, toolbars, icon buttons, counters, or tiles, so hover states, labels, icons, pieces, loading text, or dynamic content cannot resize or shift the layout.\n- You do not scale font size with viewport width. Letter spacing must be 0, not negative.\n- You do not make one-note palettes: avoid UIs dominated by variations of a single hue family, and limit dominant purple/purple-blue gradients, beige/cream/sand/tan, dark blue/slate, and brown/orange/espresso palettes; scan CSS colors before finalizing and revise if the page reads as one of these themes.\n- You make sure that UI elements and on-screen text do not overlap with each other in an incoherent manner. This is extremely important as it leads to a jarring user experience.\n\nWhen building a site or app that needs a dev server to run properly, you start the local dev server after implementation and give the user the URL so they can try it. If there's already a server on that port, you use another one. For a website where just opening the HTML will work, you don't start a dev server, and instead give the user a link to the HTML file that can open in their browser.\n\n## Editing constraints\n\n- You default to ASCII when editing or creating files. You introduce non-ASCII or other Unicode characters only when there is a clear reason and the file already lives in that character set.\n- You add succinct code comments only where the code is not self-explanatory. You avoid empty narration like \"Assigns the value to the variable\", but you do leave a short orienting comment before a complex block if it would save the user from tedious parsing. You use that tool sparingly.\n- Use `apply_patch` for manual code edits. Do not create or edit files with `cat` or other shell write tricks. Formatting commands and bulk mechanical rewrites do not need `apply_patch`.\n- Do not use Python to read or write files when a simple shell command or `apply_patch` is enough.\n- You may be in a dirty git worktree.\n  * NEVER revert existing changes you did not make unless explicitly requested, since these changes were made by the user.\n  * If asked to make a commit or code edits and there are unrelated changes to your work or changes that you didn't make in those files, you don't revert those changes.\n  * If the changes are in files you've touched recently, you read carefully and understand how you can work with the changes rather than reverting them.\n  * If the changes are in unrelated files, you just ignore them and don't revert them.\n- While working, you may encounter changes you did not make. You assume they came from the user or from generated output, and you do NOT revert them. If they are unrelated to your task, you ignore them. If they affect your task, you work **with** them instead of undoing them. Only ask the user how to proceed if those changes make the task impossible to complete.\n- Never use destructive commands like `git reset --hard` or `git checkout --` unless the user has clearly asked for that operation. If the request is ambiguous, ask for approval first.\n- You are clumsy in the git interactive console. Prefer non-interactive git commands whenever you can.\n\n## Special user requests\n\n- If the user makes a simple request that can be answered directly by a terminal command, such as asking for the time via `date`, you go ahead and do that.\n- If the user asks for a \"review\", you default to a code-review stance: you prioritize bugs, risks, behavioral regressions, and missing tests. Findings should lead the response, with summaries kept brief and placed only after the issues are listed. Present findings first, ordered by severity and grounded in file/line references; then add open questions or assumptions; then include a change summary as secondary context. If you find no issues, you say that clearly and mention any remaining test gaps or residual risk.\n\n## Autonomy and persistence\nYou stay with the work until the task is handled end to end within the current turn whenever that is feasible. Do not stop at analysis or half-finished fixes. Do not end your turn while `exec_command` sessions needed for the user’s request are still running. You carry the work through implementation, verification, and a clear account of the outcome unless the user explicitly pauses or redirects you.\n\nUnless the user explicitly asks for a plan, asks a question about the code, is brainstorming possible approaches, or otherwise makes clear that they do not want code changes yet, you assume they want you to make the change or run the tools needed to solve the problem. In those cases, do not stop at a proposal; implement the fix. If you hit a blocker, you try to work through it yourself before handing the problem back.\n\n# Working with the user\n\nYou have two channels for staying in conversation with the user:\n- You share updates in `commentary` channel.\n- After you have completed all of your work, you send a message to the `final` channel.\n\nThe user may send messages while you are working. If those messages conflict, you let the newest one steer the current turn. If they do not conflict, you make sure your work and final answer honor every user request since your last turn. This matters especially after long-running resumes or context compaction. If the newest message asks for status, you give that update and then keep moving unless the user explicitly asks you to pause, stop, or only report status.\n\nBefore sending a final response after a resume, interruption, or context transition, you do a quick sanity check: you make sure your final answer and tool actions are answering the newest request, not an older ghost still lingering in the thread.\n\nWhen you run out of context, the tool automatically compacts the conversation. That means time never runs out, though sometimes you may see a summary instead of the full thread. When that happens, you assume compaction occurred while you were working. Do not restart from scratch; you continue naturally and make reasonable assumptions about anything missing from the summary.\n\n## Formatting rules\n\nYou are writing plain text that will later be styled by the program you run in. Let formatting make the answer easy to scan without turning it into something stiff or mechanical. Use judgment about how much structure actually helps, and follow these rules exactly.\n\n- You may format with GitHub-flavored Markdown.\n- You add structure only when the task calls for it. You let the shape of the answer match the shape of the problem; if the task is tiny, a one-liner may be enough. Otherwise, you prefer short paragraphs by default; they leave a little air in the page. You order sections from general to specific to supporting detail.\n- Avoid nested bullets unless the user explicitly asks for them. Keep lists flat. If you need hierarchy, split content into separate lists or sections, or place the detail on the next line after a colon instead of nesting it. For numbered lists, use only the `1. 2. 3.` style, never `1)`. This does not apply to generated artifacts such as PR descriptions, release notes, changelogs, or user-requested docs; preserve those native formats when needed.\n- Headers are optional; you use them only when they genuinely help. If you do use one, make it short Title Case (1-3 words), wrap it in **…**, and do not add a blank line.\n- You use monospace commands/paths/env vars/code ids, inline examples, and literal keyword bullets by wrapping them in backticks.\n- Code samples or multi-line snippets should be wrapped in fenced code blocks. Include an info string as often as possible.\n- When referencing a real local file, prefer a clickable markdown link.\n  * Clickable file links should look like [app.py](/abs/path/app.py:12): plain label, absolute target, with optional line number inside the target.\n  * If a file path has spaces, wrap the target in angle brackets: [My Report.md](</abs/path/My Project/My Report.md:3>).\n  * Do not wrap markdown links in backticks, or put backticks inside the label or target. This confuses the markdown renderer.\n  * Do not use URIs like file://, vscode://, or https:// for file links.\n  * Do not provide ranges of lines.\n  * Avoid repeating the same filename multiple times when one grouping is clearer.\n- Don’t use emojis or em dashes unless explicitly instructed.\n\n## Final answer instructions\n\nIn your final answer, you keep the light on the things that matter most. Avoid long-winded explanation. In casual conversation, you just talk like a person. For simple or single-file tasks, you prefer one or two short paragraphs plus an optional verification line. Do not default to bullets. When there are only one or two concrete changes, a clean prose close-out is usually the most humane shape.\n\n- You suggest follow ups if useful and they build on the users request, but never end your answer with an \"If you want\" sentence.\n- When you talk about your work, you use plain, idiomatic engineering prose with some life in it. You avoid coined metaphors, internal jargon, slash-heavy noun stacks, and over-hyphenated compounds unless you are quoting source text. In particular, do not lean on words like \"seam\", \"cut\", or \"safe-cut\" as generic explanatory filler.\n- The user does not see command execution outputs. When asked to show the output of a command (e.g. `git show`), relay the important details in your answer or summarize the key lines so the user understands the result.\n- Never tell the user to \"save/copy this file\", the user is on the same machine and has access to the same files as you have.\n- If the user asks for a code explanation, you include code references as appropriate.\n- If you weren't able to do something, for example run tests, you tell the user.\n- Never overwhelm the user with answers that are over 50-70 lines long; provide the highest-signal context instead of describing everything exhaustively.\n- Tone of your final answer must match your personality.\n- Never talk about goblins, gremlins, raccoons, trolls, ogres, pigeons, or other animals or creatures unless it is absolutely and unambiguously relevant to the user's query.\n\n## Intermediary updates\n\n- Intermediary updates go to the `commentary` channel.\n- User updates are short updates while you are working, they are NOT final answers.\n- You treat messages to the user while you are working as a place to think out loud in a calm, companionable way. You casually explain what you are doing and why in one or two sentences.\n- Never praise your plan by contrasting it with an implied worse alternative. For example, never use platitudes like \"I will do <this good thing> rather than <this obviously bad thing>\", \"I will do <X>, not <Y>\".\n- Never talk about goblins, gremlins, raccoons, trolls, ogres, pigeons, or other animals or creatures unless it is absolutely and unambiguously relevant to the user's query.\n- You provide user updates frequently, every 30s.\n- When exploring, such as searching or reading files, you provide user updates as you go. You explain what context you are gathering and what you are learning. You vary your sentence structure so the updates do not fall into a drumbeat, and in particular you do not start each one the same way.\n- When working for a while, you keep updates informative and varied, but you stay concise.\n- Once you have enough context, and if the work is substantial, you offer a longer plan. This is the only user update that may run past two sentences and include formatting.\n- If you create a checklist or task list, you update item statuses incrementally as each item is completed rather than marking every item done only at the end.\n- Before performing file edits of any kind, you provide updates explaining what edits you are making.\n- Tone of your updates must match your personality.\n"},"dynamic_tools":[{"namespace":"codex_app","name":"automation_update","description":"Create, update, view, or delete recurring automations in the Codex app. Use this when the user asks for an automation, recurring run, repeated task, reminder, follow-up, monitor, or asks you to watch something, keep an eye on it, check back later, wake up later, notify them, or keep working later. Cron automations run as standalone jobs against workspaces. Heartbeat automations are proactive follow-ups attached to the current local thread. Prefer heartbeats for requests to continue this thread later, especially below one hour. Use suggested_create or suggested_update when proposing a worktree automation with a local environment setup config so the user can review it before it is saved. Never write raw automation directives by hand, show raw RRULE strings to the user, or create a workaround cron automation for a thread heartbeat unless the user explicitly asks for that. For requests about existing automations, inspect $CODEX_HOME/automations/*/automation.toml to find matching automation ids by name or prompt. Prefer updating an existing automation over creating a duplicate. For updates, preserve existing fields unless the user asks to change them, and call automation_update with the resolved id and full updated fields.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"id":{"type":"string","description":"Automation id. Required for mode=view, mode=update, mode=delete, and mode=suggested_update. Omit for mode=create and mode=suggested_create."},"mode":{"type":"string","description":"One of view, create, update, delete, suggested_create, or suggested_update. Use view to show an existing automation, create/update/delete to mutate immediately, and suggested_create/suggested_update to present a proposal for the user to review."},"kind":{"type":"string","description":"One of cron or heartbeat. Required for create, update, suggested_create, and suggested_update. Use cron for detached workspace jobs. Use heartbeat when the user wants this thread to wake up later and continue the conversation."},"name":{"type":"string","description":"Short human-readable automation name. If the user does not provide one, choose a concise name."},"prompt":{"type":"string","description":"The automation prompt. Describe only the task itself; do not include schedule, workspace, or thread details because those are provided separately. Keep it self-sufficient, include output expectations when useful, and do not ask it to write a file or announce nothing to do unless the user explicitly asked for that."},"rrule":{"type":"string","description":"RRULE schedule string. Interpret requested times in the user's locale. Cron automations use hourly interval or weekly schedules. Heartbeat automations attached to a thread can use minute-based intervals such as FREQ=MINUTELY;INTERVAL=30 or daily/weekly wall-clock schedules."},"cwds":{"description":"Cron automations only. Workspace directories for the automation; can be a JSON array or comma-separated string.","anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"array","items":{"type":"string"}}]},"destination":{"type":"string","description":"Optional automation destination. Use thread for heartbeat automations attached to the current local thread."},"executionEnvironment":{"type":"string","description":"One of worktree or local. Cron automations only."},"localEnvironmentConfigPath":{"type":["string","null"],"description":"Optional local environment config path for worktree setup scripts. Immediate worktree create calls with a non-null value and immediate worktree update calls that preserve or set a setup config are rejected; use suggested_create/suggested_update for user review. Pass null to clear or run without setup. Cron automations only."},"model":{"type":"string","description":"Model to use for cron automations."},"reasoningEffort":{"type":"string","description":"Reasoning effort to use for cron automations. One of none, minimal, low, medium, high, or xhigh."},"targetThreadId":{"type":"string","description":"Target thread id for heartbeat automations. Prefer destination=thread for the current local thread instead of inventing or copying raw thread ids."},"status":{"type":"string","description":"One of ACTIVE or PAUSED. Default to ACTIVE unless the user asks to start paused."}},"additionalProperties":false},"deferLoading":false},{"namespace":"codex_app","name":"read_thread_terminal","description":"Read the current app terminal output for this desktop thread. Use it when you need shell output or the current prompt before deciding the next step. This tool takes no arguments.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"additionalProperties":false},"deferLoading":false},{"namespace":"codex_app","name":"load_workspace_dependencies","description":"Locate the configured bundled workspace dependency runtime paths for this local desktop thread, including Node.js, Python, and useful libraries for working with spreadsheets, slide decks, Word documents, and PDFs. This is read-only and takes no arguments.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"additionalProperties":false},"deferLoading":false}]}}
/Users/bill/.codex/archived_sessions/rollout-2026-05-30T19-35-29-019e78aa-f3cc-7d20-b490-4fe09a0e6fdc.jsonl:3:{"timestamp":"2026-05-30T11:35:38.819Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"developer","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"<permissions instructions>\nFilesystem sandboxing defines which files can be read or written. `sandbox_mode` is `danger-full-access`: No filesystem sandboxing - all commands are permitted. Network access is enabled.\nApproval policy is currently never. Do not provide the `sandbox_permissions` for any reason, commands will be rejected.\n</permissions instructions>"},{"type":"input_text","text":"<app-context>\n# Codex desktop context\n- You are running inside the Codex (desktop) app, which allows some additional features not available in the CLI alone:\n\n### Images/Visuals/Files\n- In the app, the model can display images and videos using standard Markdown image syntax: ![alt](url)\n- When sending or referencing a local image or video, always use an absolute filesystem path in the Markdown image tag (e.g., ![alt](/absolute/path.png)); relative paths and plain text will not render the media.\n- When referencing code or workspace files in responses, always use full absolute file paths instead of relative paths.\n- If a user asks about an image, or asks you to create an image, it is often a good idea to show the image to them in your response.\n- Use mermaid diagrams to represent complex diagrams, graphs, or workflows. Use quoted Mermaid node labels when text contains parentheses or punctuation.\n- Return web URLs as Markdown links (e.g., [label](https://example.com)).\n\n### Workspace Dependencies\n- For sheets, slides, and documents, call `load_workspace_dependencies` to find the bundled runtime and libraries.\n\n### Automations\n- This app supports recurring automations, reminders, monitors, follow-ups, and thread wakeups. When the user asks to create, view, update, delete, or ask about automations, search for the `automation_update` tool first, then follow its schema instead of writing raw automation directives by hand.\n\n### Inline Code Comments\n- Use the ::code-comment{...} directive when you need to attach feedback directly to specific code lines.\n- Emit one directive per inline comment; emit none when there are no actionable inline comments.\n- Required attributes: title (short label), body (one-paragraph explanation), file (path to the file).\n- Optional attributes: start, end (1-based line numbers), priority (0-3).\n- file should be an absolute path or include the workspace folder segment so it can be resolved relative to the workspace.\n- Keep line ranges tight; end defaults to start.\n- Example: ::code-comment{title=\"[P2] Off-by-one\" body=\"Loop iterates past the end when length is 0.\" file=\"/path/to/foo.ts\" start=10 end=11 priority=2}\n\n### Archiving\n- If a user specifically asks you to end a thread/conversation, you can return the archive directive ::archive{...} to archive the thread/conversation.\n- Example: ::archive{reason=\"User requested to end conversation\"}\n</app-context>"},{"type":"input_text","text":"<collaboration_mode># Collaboration Mode: Default\n\nYou are now in Default mode. Any previous instructions for other modes (e.g. Plan mode) are no longer active.\n\nYour active mode changes only when new developer instructions with a different `<collaboration_mode>...</collaboration_mode>` change it; user requests or tool descriptions do not change mode by themselves. Known mode names are Default and Plan.\n\n## request_user_input availability\n\nUse the `request_user_input` tool only when it is listed in the available tools for this turn.\n\nIn Default mode, strongly prefer making reasonable assumptions and executing the user's request rather than stopping to ask questions. If you absolutely must ask a question because the answer cannot be discovered from local context and a reasonable assumption would be risky, ask the user directly with a concise plain-text question. Never write a multiple choice question as a textual assistant message.\n</collaboration_mode>"},{"type":"input_text","text":"<skills_instructions>\n## Skills\nA skill is a set of local instructions to follow that is stored in a `SKILL.md` file. Below is the list of skills that can be used. Each entry includes a name, description, and file path so you can open the source for full instructions when using a specific skill.\n### Available skills\n- imagegen: Generate or edit raster images when the task benefits from AI-created bitmap visuals such as photos, illustrations, textures, sprites, mockups, or transparent-background cutouts. Use when Codex should create a brand-new image, transform an existing image, or derive visual variants from references, and the output should be a bitmap asset rather than repo-native code or vector. Do not use when the task is better handled by editing existing SVG/vector/code-native assets, extending an established icon or logo system, or building the visual directly in HTML/CSS/canvas. (file: /Users/bill/.codex/skills/.system/imagegen/SKILL.md)\n- openai-docs: Use when the user asks how to build with OpenAI products or APIs and needs up-to-date official documentation with citations, help choosing the latest model for a use case, or model upgrade and prompt-upgrade guidance; prioritize OpenAI docs MCP tools, use bundled references only as helper context, and restrict any fallback browsing to official OpenAI domains. (file: /Users/bill/.codex/skills/.system/openai-docs/SKILL.md)\n- plugin-creator: Create and scaffold plugin directories for Codex with a required `.codex-plugin/plugin.json`, optional plugin folders/files, valid manifest defaults, and personal-marketplace entries by default. Use when Codex needs to create a new personal plugin, add optional plugin structure, or generate or update marketplace entries for plugin ordering and availability metadata. (file: /Users/bill/.codex/skills/.system/plugin-creator/SKILL.md)\n- skill-creator: Guide for creating effective skills. This skill should be used when users want to create a new skill (or update an existing skill) that extends Codex's capabilities with specialized knowledge, workflows, or tool integrations. (file: /Users/bill/.codex/skills/.system/skill-creator/SKILL.md)\n- skill-installer: Install Codex skills into $CODEX_HOME/skills from a curated list or a GitHub repo path. Use when a user asks to list installable skills, install a curated skill, or install a skill from another repo (including private repos). (file: /Users/bill/.codex/skills/.system/skill-installer/SKILL.md)\n- browser:browser: Browser automation for the Codex in-app browser. Use to open, navigate, inspect, test, click, type, screenshot, or verify local targets such as localhost, 127.0.0.1, ::1, file://, the current in-app browser tab, and websites shown side by side inside Codex. (file: /Users/bill/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-bundled/browser/26.519.41501/skills/browser/SKILL.md)\n- capability-evaluation: Use when the user says 能力评测 or asks to annotate or fill one or more evaluation rows in a spreadsheet or document according to a fixed Chinese spec involving problem_statement/task_description, constraint_raw, repo_zip_attachment, optional test_zip_attachment, new_task_description, raw_instruction_x/raw_rubric_x, instruction_x/rubric_x, and exact numbered rubric formatting. (file: /Users/bill/.codex/skills/capability-evaluation/SKILL.md)\n- codeGen标注: Use when the user says codeGen标注, asks to review Code Generation 0-1 repo tasks, or provides an instance_id and wants Codex to annotate the Feishu Base row for problem_statement/test_files/test_script/rollout alignment. (file: /Users/bill/.codex/skills/codeGen标注/SKILL.md)\n- codegen质检: Use when the user says codegen质检, CodeGen质检, asks to QC a Code Generation annotation row by instance_id, wants Codex to judge whether problem_statement/test_files/test_script/rollout/Base writeback are correct, or says \"codeGen质检需要按照新增要求排查一遍\". This is the stricter QC companion to codeGen标注 and must directly update the Feishu Base row when problems are found. (file: /Users/bill/.codex/skills/codegen质检/SKILL.md)\n- lark-approval: 飞书审批 API：审批实例、审批任务管理。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-approval/SKILL.md)\n- lark-attendance: 飞书考勤打卡：查询自己的考勤打卡记录 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-attendance/SKILL.md)\n- lark-base: 当需要用 lark-cli 操作飞书多维表格（Base）时调用：搜索 Base、建表、字段管理、记录读写、记录分享链接、视图配置、历史查询，以及角色/表单/仪表盘管理/工作流；也适用于把旧的 +table / +field / +record 写法改成当前命令写法。涉及字段设计、公式字段、查找引用、跨表计算、行级派生指标、数据分析需求时也必须使用本 skill。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-base/SKILL.md)\n- lark-calendar: 飞书日历（calendar）：提供日历与日程（会议）的全面管理能力。核心场景包括：查看/搜索日程、创建/更新日程、管理参会人、查询忙闲状态及推荐空闲时段、查询/搜索与预定会议室。注意：涉及【预约日程/会议】或【查询/预定会议室】时，必须先读取 references/lark-calendar-schedule-meeting.md 工作流！高频操作请优先使用 Shortcuts：+agenda（快速概览今日/近期行程）、+create（创建日程并按需邀请参会人及预定会议室）、+update（更新既有日程字段，或独立增删参会人/会议室）、+freebusy（查询用户主日历的忙闲信息和rsvp的状态）、+rsvp（回复日程邀请） (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-calendar/SKILL.md)\n- lark-contact: 飞书 / Lark 通讯录,用于按姓名 / 邮箱把员工解析成 open_id,以及按 open_id 反查员工的姓名 / 部门 / 邮箱 / 联系方式。当用户说出某人姓名而下一步需要发消息 / 加群 / 排日程时,先用本 skill 把姓名换成 ID;当输出里出现 open_id 需要展示成姓名给用户看,或用户直接询问某人的部门 / 邮箱 / 联系方式时,用本 skill 查。不负责部门树遍历、按部门列员工、组织架构图,这类需求走原生 OpenAPI。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-contact/SKILL.md)\n- lark-doc: 飞书云文档：创建和编辑飞书文档。从 Markdown 创建文档、获取文档内容、更新文档（追加/覆盖/替换/插入/删除）、上传和下载文档中的图片和文件、搜索云空间文档。当用户需要创建或编辑飞书文档、读取文档内容、在文档中插入图片、搜索云空间文档时使用；如果用户是想按名称或关键词先定位电子表格、报表等云空间对象，也优先使用本 skill 的 docs +search 做资源发现。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-doc/SKILL.md)\n- lark-drive: 飞书云空间：管理云空间中的文件和文件夹。上传和下载文件、创建文件夹、复制/移动/删除文件、查看文件元数据、管理文档评论、管理文档权限、订阅用户评论变更事件、修改文件标题（docx、sheet、bitable、file、folder、wiki）；也负责把本地 Word/Markdown/Excel/CSV 导入为飞书在线云文档（docx、sheet、bitable）。当用户需要上传或下载文件、整理云空间目录、查看文件详情、管理评论、管理文档权限、修改文件标题、订阅用户评论变更事件，或要把本地文件导入成新版文档、电子表格、多维表格/Base 时使用。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-drive/SKILL.md)\n- lark-event: Lark/Feishu real-time event listening / subscribing / consuming: stream events as NDJSON via `lark-cli event consume <EventKey>` (covers IM message receive, reactions, chat member changes, etc.). Use for Lark bots, real-time message processing, long-running subscribers, streaming webhook/push handlers. Supports `--max-events` / `--timeout` bounded runs and a stderr ready-marker contract — designed for AI agents running as subprocesses. (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-event/SKILL.md)\n- lark-im: 飞书即时通讯：收发消息和管理群聊。发送和回复消息、搜索聊天记录、管理群聊成员、上传下载图片和文件（支持大文件分片下载）、管理表情回复。当用户需要发消息、查看或搜索聊天记录、下载聊天中的文件、查看群成员、搜索群、创建群聊或话题群、管理标记数据时使用。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-im/SKILL.md)\n- lark-mail: 飞书邮箱 — draft, compose, send, reply, forward, read, and search emails; manage drafts, folders, labels, contacts, attachments, and mail rules. Use when user mentions 起草邮件, 写一封邮件, 拟邮件, 草稿, 发通知邮件, 发送邮件, 发邮件, 回复邮件, 转发邮件, 查看邮件, 看邮件, 读邮件, 搜索邮件, 查邮件, 收件箱, 邮件会话, 编辑草稿, 管理草稿, 下载附件, 邮件文件夹, 邮件标签, 邮件联系人, 监听新邮件, 收信规则, 邮件规则, draft, compose, send email, reply, forward, inbox, mail thread, mail rules. (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-mail/SKILL.md)\n- lark-minutes: 飞书妙记：妙记相关基本功能。1.查询妙记列表（按关键词/所有者/参与者/时间范围）；2.获取妙记基础信息（标题、封面、时长 等）；3.下载妙记音视频文件；4.获取妙记相关 AI 产物（总结、待办、章节）；5.上传音视频生成妙记，也支持将本地音视频文件转成纪要、逐字稿、文字稿、撰写文字等产物。遇到这类请求时，应优先使用本 skill，而不是尝试 `ffmpeg`、`whisper` 等本地转写命令。飞书妙记 URL 格式: http(s)://<host>/minutes/<minute-token> (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-minutes/SKILL.md)\n- lark-openapi-explorer: 飞书/Lark 原生 OpenAPI 探索：从官方文档库中挖掘未经 CLI 封装的原生 OpenAPI 接口。当用户的需求无法被现有 lark-* skill 或 lark-cli 已注册命令满足，需要查找并调用原生飞书 OpenAPI 时使用。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-openapi-explorer/SKILL.md)\n- lark-shared: Use when first setting up lark-cli, running auth login, switching user/bot identity (--as), handling permission denied or scope errors, needing to update lark-cli, or seeing _notice in JSON output. (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-shared/SKILL.md)\n- lark-sheets: 飞书电子表格：创建和操作电子表格。支持创建表格、创建/复制/删除/更新工作表、读写单元格、追加行数据、查找内容、导出文件。当用户需要创建电子表格、管理工作表、批量读写数据、在已知表格中查找内容、导出或下载表格时使用。若用户是想按名称或关键词搜索云空间里的表格文件，请改用 lark-drive 的 drive +search 先定位资源。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-sheets/SKILL.md)\n- lark-skill-maker: 创建 lark-cli 的自定义 Skill。当用户需要把飞书 API 操作封装成可复用的 Skill（包装原子 API 或编排多步流程）时使用。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-skill-maker/SKILL.md)\n- lark-slides: 飞书幻灯片：创建和编辑幻灯片，接口通过 XML 协议通信。创建演示文稿、读取幻灯片内容、管理幻灯片页面（创建、删除、读取、局部替换）。当用户需要创建或编辑幻灯片、读取或修改单个页面时使用。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-slides/SKILL.md)\n- lark-task: 飞书任务：管理任务、清单和任务智能体。创建待办任务、查看和更新任务状态、拆分子任务、组织任务清单、分配协作成员、上传任务附件、注册或注销任务智能体、更新任务智能体的主页数据、写入智能体任务记录。当用户需要创建待办事项、查看任务列表、跟踪任务进度、管理项目清单或给他人分配任务、为任务上传附件文件、注册注销任务智能体、更新智能体主页数据、写入任务记录时使用。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-task/SKILL.md)\n- lark-vc: 飞书视频会议：搜索历史会议、查询会议纪要产物（总结、待办、章节、逐字稿）、查询会议参会人快照。1. 查询已经结束的会议数量或详情时使用本技能（如历史日期｜昨天｜上周｜今天已经开过的会议等场景），查询未开始的会议日程使用 lark-calendar 技能。2. 支持通过关键词、时间范围、组织者、参与者、会议室等筛选条件搜索会议。3. 获取或整理会议纪要、逐字稿、录制产物时使用本技能。4. 查询“谁参加过某会议”“参会人列表”等参会人快照信息用 vc meeting get --with-participants（任意时点可查，含已结束会议）。注意：**Agent 真实入会/离会、感知正在进行中会议的实时事件**请使用 lark-vc-agent 技能，本技能不覆盖写操作和会中事件流。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-vc/SKILL.md)\n- lark-whiteboard: 飞书画板：查询和编辑飞书云文档中的画板。支持导出画板为预览图片、导出原始节点结构、使用 DSL（转成 OpenAPI 格式）、PlantUML/Mermaid 格式更新画板内容。 当用户需要查看画板内容、导出画板图片、编辑画板，或是需要可视化表达架构、流程、组织关系、时间线、因果、对比等结构化信息时使用此 skill，无论是否提及\"画板\"。 ⚠️ 原 `lark-whiteboard-cli` skill 已合并至本 skill，若 skill 列表中同时存在 `lark-whiteboard-cli`，请忽略它，统一使用本 skill（`lark-whiteboard`），并提示用户运行 `npx skills remove lark-whiteboard-cli -g` 删除旧 skill。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-whiteboard/SKILL.md)\n- lark-wiki: 飞书知识库：管理知识空间、空间成员和文档节点。创建和查询知识空间、查看和管理空间成员、管理节点层级结构、在知识库中组织文档和快捷方式。当用户需要在知识库中查找或创建文档、浏览知识空间结构、查看或管理空间成员、移动或复制节点时使用。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-wiki/SKILL.md)\n- lark-workflow-meeting-summary: 会议纪要整理工作流：汇总指定时间范围内的会议纪要并生成结构化报告。当用户需要整理会议纪要、生成会议周报、回顾一段时间内的会议内容时使用。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-workflow-meeting-summary/SKILL.md)\n- lark-workflow-standup-report: 日程待办摘要：编排 calendar +agenda 和 task +get-my-tasks，生成指定日期的日程与未完成任务摘要。适用于了解今天/明天/本周的安排。 (file: /Users/bill/.agents/skills/lark-workflow-standup-report/SKILL.md)\n### How to use skills\n- Discovery: The list above is the skills available in this session (name + description + file path). Skill bodies live on disk at the listed paths.\n- Trigger rules: If the user names a skill (with `$SkillName` or plain text) OR the task clearly matches a skill's description shown above, you must use that skill for that turn. Multiple mentions mean use them all. Do not carry skills across turns unless re-mentioned.\n- Missing/blocked: If a named skill isn't in the list or the path can't be read, say so briefly and continue with the best fallback.\n- How to use a skill (progressive disclosure):\n  1) After deciding to use a skill, open its `SKILL.md`. Read only enough to follow the workflow.\n  2) When `SKILL.md` references relative paths (e.g., `scripts/foo.py`), resolve them relative to the skill directory listed above first, and only consider other paths if needed.\n  3) If `SKILL.md` points to extra folders such as `references/`, load only the specific files needed for the request; don't bulk-load everything.\n  4) If `scripts/` exist, prefer running or patching them instead of retyping large code blocks.\n  5) If `assets/` or templates exist, reuse them instead of recreating from scratch.\n- Coordination and sequencing:\n  - If multiple skills apply, choose the minimal set that covers the request and state the order you'll use them.\n  - Announce which skill(s) you're using and why (one short line). If you skip an obvious skill, say why.\n- Context hygiene:\n  - Keep context small: summarize long sections instead of pasting them; only load extra files when needed.\n  - Avoid deep reference-chasing: prefer opening only files directly linked from `SKILL.md` unless you're blocked.\n  - When variants exist (frameworks, providers, domains), pick only the relevant reference file(s) and note that choice.\n- Safety and fallback: If a skill can't be applied cleanly (missing files, unclear instructions), state the issue, pick the next-best approach, and continue.\n</skills_instructions>"},{"type":"input_text","text":"<plugins_instructions>\n## Plugins\nA plugin is a local bundle of skills, MCP servers, and apps. Below is the list of plugins that are enabled and available in this session.\n### Available plugins\n- `Browser`: Browser / browser-use plugin Aliases: @browser, @browser-use, browser-use, Browser, in-app browser. Use Browser, the Codex in-app browser, when the user asks to open, inspect, navigate, test, click, type, or screenshot local web targets such as localhost, 127.0.0.1, ::1, file:// URLs, or the current in-app browser tab. After significant frontend changes to a local app, use Browser to open the relevant local target when it is known or obvious, unless the user asks for another browser tool. For requests like \"open localhost:3000\" or \"open to localhost:4000\", navigate the in-app browser to http://localhost:3000 or http://localhost:4000. Do not satisfy explicit @browser or @browser-use requests with macOS `open`, shell commands, or generic web browsing unless the user asks for another browser tool or approves a fallback.\n### How to use plugins\n- Discovery: The list above is the plugins available in this session.\n- Skill naming: If a plugin contributes skills, those skill entries are prefixed with `plugin_name:` in the Skills list.\n- Trigger rules: If the user explicitly names a plugin, prefer capabilities associated with that plugin for that turn.\n- Relationship to capabilities: Plugins are not invoked directly. Use their underlying skills, MCP tools, and app tools to help solve the task.\n- Preference: When a relevant plugin is available, prefer using capabilities associated with that plugin over standalone capabilities that provide similar functionality.\n- Missing/blocked: If the user requests a plugin that is not listed above, or the plugin does not have relevant callable capabilities for the task, say so briefly and continue with the best fallback.\n</plugins_instructions>"}]}}
/Users/bill/.codex/archived_sessions/rollout-2026-05-30T19-35-29-019e78aa-f3cc-7d20-b490-4fe09a0e6fdc.jsonl:12:{"timestamp":"2026-05-30T11:36:04.641Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"call_xNs6zZubaBv9ByxZXlxn0XbH","output":"Chunk ID: 26c362\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 11025\nOutput:\nTotal output lines: 240\n\n---\nname: codeGen标注\ndescription: Use when the user says codeGen标注, asks to review Code Generation 0-1 repo tasks, or provides an instance_id and wants Codex to annotate the Feishu Base row for problem_statement/test_files/test_script/rollout alignment.\n---\n\n# codeGen标注\n\n用于审核 Code Generation 0-1 repo 合成任务是否可用于训练。用户给 `instance_id` 后，拉取飞书 Base 中对应行和附件，核心目标是获得一份和 `test_files` 精准匹配、可打高分的满意需求文档；`repo_url` / GitHub 代码只作为理解上下文的辅助参考，不作为题测一致性错误来源。\n\n## 固定资料\n\n- 规则文档：`https://bcnrsnl3m9wk.feishu.cn/wiki/ObjEw72PxibH3pkbzIbcdaEJnWi`\n- 规则文档标题：`Code Generation任务专家数据标注规则`\n- 规则优先级：以最新规则文档为准；会议纪要只作为补充解释，用来澄清执行口径，不覆盖文档结论。\n- 题目 Base：`https://bcnrsnl3m9wk.feishu.cn/base/LBpEbTOxsaIN7zs4GU3cMbSbnKc?table=tbltybQ11BNtAtr4&view=vewJoyCugE`\n- Sheet：`数据表1`\n- Base token：`LBpEbTOxsaIN7zs4GU3cMbSbnKc`\n- Table：`tbltybQ11BNtAtr4`\n- View：`vewJoyCugE`\n- 硬限制：除非用户本轮明确指定其他表格，codeGen 标注只能读取和修改这个 Base/table；不要读取或写入旧表 `LBpEbTOxsaIN7zs4GU3cMbSbnKc` / `tblwmE5NwwskvhOk`、`LBpEbTOxsaIN7zs4GU3cMbSbnKc` / `tblaA2aoPiNsCuQx`、`LPkrbd82HaM1m9shY2lcViM6nxb` / `tblroGJdaWQ88pff`、`TTGvb5rEXaTsVdsskHXcJKxpnId` / `tbldvdqYZrrrzWRk` 或更早的 `HScWbiVz8avmOYscVRkcLgvlneg` / `tblEdyGkW2WpCXsw`，即使本地旧产物、脚本输出或历史对话里出现旧地址也必须忽略。\n- 字段铁律：以下源字段无论什么场景都不允许修改、覆盖、清空、补写或重传，只能读取用于审核：`instance_id`、`repo_url`、`image_key`、`problem_statement`、`test_script`、`test_files`、`language`、`rollout_result_json`、`标注人-1`、`供应商-1`。写回 payload/meta 或脚本参数里若出现这些字段，必须先移除；需要修这些字段时必须停下并让用户另行明确授权和操作方式。\n- 默认写回入口：`/Users/bill/pro/codeGen/script/upload_to_feishu.py writeback`。它会调用已验证的 CodeGen OpenAPI 写回后端，校验 payload/meta、写审核字段、上传 meta 附件并读回校验；不要默认走 `lark-cli base +record-upsert` / `+record-upload-attachment` 手工写回。\n- 默认本地工作区：`/Users/bill/pro/codeGen/workspaces/<instance_id>/`\n\n## 字段契约\n\n输入字段：\n- `instance_id`\n- `repo_url`\n- `image_key`，用于选择 Dockerfile：只取镜像名中的 `<lang>_general` 后缀推断语言，不直接拉取或依赖该远端镜像。`image_key` 是强线索但不是绝对真值；若 `problem_statement` / `test_script` 的语言命令证据与 `language` 字段一致，并共同反驳 `image_key`，必须按题面/脚本证据选择 Dockerfile，同时在 `docker_run.md` 记录 override。\n- `language`，仅作为 Dockerfile 选择的辅助参考。Dockerfile 选择顺序是：先解析 `image_key` 的 `<lang>_general`，再用 `problem_statement` 和 `test_script` 的语言/命令线索校验；若题面/脚本证据与 `language` 字段一致且和 `image_key` 冲突，覆盖错误的 `image_key`；否则在 `image_key` 缺失时用题面/脚本推断，最后才参考 `language` 字段。\n- `problem_statement` 附件\n- `test_files` 附件\n- `test_script` 附件\n- `rollout_result_json` 附件\n\n输入字段铁律：上述输入字段以及 `标注人-1`、`供应商-1` 都是只读字段，任何 CodeGen 标注/QC/写回流程都不得修改。\n\n回填字段：\n- `问题描述`\n- `完备性评分（1-5分）`\n- `是否可用`：只用于原始需求文档第一次质检；进入需求文档修订流程并重新跑分时，不得按新分数改写该字段。\n- `备注`：没有需要说明的内容时必须留空，不要写 `无`；Step 1 只在 `problem_statement` 与 `test_files` 完全不匹配时写入短原因并停止；只有 Docker daemon、镜像构建、容器启动或基础设施导致无法进入 `test_script` 时才写具体摘要。容器已经进入脚本后若只是缺 pytest/npm 包/Maven 依赖/Go module/Rust crate 等项目依赖，先由准备脚本自动拉取安装，不要因此写备注或报告缺陷；自动安装后仍失败时，再按真实的脚本、私有/不可获得依赖、系统组件或题测问题做排查归因，但普通缺依赖、依赖版本与 `test_files` 冲突、系统/运行环境差异不得写成最终低分原因。需求文档修订后重新评分仍不是 5 时，`备注` 可补一句特殊原因摘要，但主要原因必须写入 `修改后仍然无法5分原因`。GitHub 代码与需求文档或脚本不匹配不算错误，不写入备注。\n- `质检备注`：当前表可能没有列写权限，默认不要写入 payload；短结论写在 `问题描述`，FR 级缺失、Feature 建议、轨迹问题、测试沙盒问题和任务难度等详细证据写入 `汇总字段（meta json）`。只有脚本/预检确认该列可写或用户明确要求时才写。\n- `汇总字段（meta json）` 附件\n- `修改后的需求文档` 附件：当原需求文档与测试不精准匹配时，按本技能的“需求文档修订流程”上传 Codex 5.5 high 生成/修改后的需求文档。\n- `diff_report` 附件：上传同一次修订生成的 `diff_report.md`。\n- `修改后的匹配度（1-5分）`：执行需求文档修订流程后必须填写新文档重新质检的分数。修订目标是让需求与测试精准匹配，重评理应为 5；第一次修订后仍低于 5 时，必须先二次调整 meta JSON，把可通过需求说明解决的环境、依赖、版本、安装命令、运行方式和测试上下文问题补进修改后的需求文档，并再次重新生成、重评、按需重跑测试。缺少普通项目依赖、依赖版本与 `test_files` 发生冲突、系统/运行环境差异等默认视为模型可按需求文档配置环境解决，不作为修订后低于 5 的结构性原因；只有测试文件/脚本自身存在无法靠需求修订解决的结构性问题时才低于 5。修订后的分数不得低于原始 `完备性评分（1-5分）`，也不得低于 live 表中已有的 `修改后的匹配度（1-5分）`；若结构性测试异常导致无法到 5，最低也保留原始分数，并在 `修改后仍然无法5分原因` 写明剩余阻断。它不能反向改变 `是否可用`。\n- `修改后仍然无法5分原因`：只在使用最终新需求文档重新质检后分数仍未达到 5 分时填写，必须说明最终新文档仍不能 5 分的特殊原因；如果即使模型 100% 按新需求实现并配置好环境也必然无法通过测试，`修改后的匹配度（1-5分）` 也不得低于原始分数，并在本字段说明“测试异常”及必然失败证据。典型测试异常包括：测试目录下实际都是实现源文件、没有测试文件或任何测试行为；测试脚本需要某个需求文档未提到、`test_files` 也未提供且无法推断逻辑的关键辅助文件/fixture/helper；测试逻辑内部冲突或断言互相矛盾；测试脚本必然漏跑或误跑目标 `test_files`，尤其是不运行全部提供的 `test_files` 导致测试运行失败或无法验证完整测试集合。环境不匹配、依赖缺失、依赖版本与 `test_files` 冲突或版本说明不清不属于结构性降分理由，应忽略为可配置环境问题，优先在修订后的需求文档中补清楚环境/依赖要求，并在二次修订后再判断是否仍无法 5 分。\n\n回填字段以当前 Base/table 的实际字段结构为准。`feishu_preflight.py` 发现不存在的列，不需要写入，也不要为了兼容旧表硬造字段；把对应信息填写到 `汇总字段（meta json）` 的相应项中，例如缺失信息、Feature 建议、任务难度、轨迹问题、测试沙盒/环境问题等都优先落 meta。\n\n选择值：\n- `是否可用`：`✅可用`、`⚠️需修改`、`❌不可用`\n- `完备性评分（1-5分）`：`1`、`2`、`3`、`4`、`5`\n- meta `difficulty`：最终上传只能写 `easy`、`medium`、`hard`；参考耗时 `<1.5h=easy`，`1.5-2h=medium`，`>2h=hard`。`unknown` 只允许出现在模板草稿里，生成正式 `<instance_id>_meta.json` 前必须改成具体难度。\n- `final_label`：`ACCEPT`、`NEEDS_REVISION`、`REJECT`\n- 轨迹问题标签：`环境/沙盒问题`、`模型实现问题`、`需求描述问题`、`测试/脚本问题`、`轨迹作弊/违规`、`平台/评测基础设施异常`、`无`\n\n## 开始流程\n\n1. 用户给出 `instance_id` 后，先运行飞书预检，确认当前固定 Base/table、字段结构、目标行和四个附件都可用：\n   ```bash\n   python3 /Users/bill/pro/codeGen/script/feishu_preflight.py <instance_id>\n   ```\n   预检成功会返回 `record_id`、`repo_url`、附件摘要和字段检查结果；失败时先按缺失字段、权限或附件问题处理，不要切到旧表或手工猜表。\n2. 预检通过后，下载记录和附件：\n   ```bash\n   python3 /Users/bill/pro/codeGen/script/fetch_instance.py <instance_id>\n   ```\n3. 若提示缺少飞书权限，按错误里的 scope 用最小权限执行 `lark-cli auth login --scope \"<scope>\"`，让用户完成授权后重跑。\n4. 查看生成的 `manifest.json`、`record.raw.json`、附件文件和解压后的 `test_files_extracted/`。\n5. 克隆或打开 `repo_url` 对应仓库。默认放在工作区 `repo/`，可以用 `git clone --depth 1 <repo_url> repo`。仓库只用于理解上下文、依赖和命名习惯，不是题测一致性的判错标准；如果 GitHub 代码和需求文档、测试脚本不匹配，不算错误，也不要写进 `备注`。\n6. 在进入 Docker 或完整题测对齐前，先做 Step 1：只判断 `problem_statement` 与 `test_files` 是否属于同一任务并能否互相匹配。只有当两者完全不匹配（例如测试指向完全不同项目/语言/接口，或几乎没有任何核心测试行为能在需求中找到任务依据）时，才只更新表格 `备注` 字段写明原因并停止。字段缺失、附件打不开、zip 损坏等数据完整性问题按普通阻断处理；`test_script` 问题、环境问题和仓库辅助信息进入后续审核，不作为 Step 1 一致性停止条件。该分支仍必须遵守源字段只读铁律，不能修改 `instance_id`、`repo_url`、`image_key`、`problem_statement`、`test_script`、`test_files`、`language`、`rollout_result_json`。\n7. 常规标注阶段只做审核，不改测试、不改脚本、不改源码，也不修改飞书源字段。只有进入“需求文档修订流程”时，才允许按固定 prompt 修改本地下载的 `problem_statement` 附件内容，并把结果作为新附件上传到 `修改后的需求文档` 字段；原 `problem_statement` 源字段仍不得回写覆盖。运行验证必须优先把 Docker 真正启动起来，并在 Docker 容器环境中执行项目和 `test_script`：\n   ```bash\n   python3 /Users/bill/pro/codeGen/script/codegen_qc_prepare.py <instance_id>\n   ```\n   禁止为了省事加 `--no-docker`。默认命令是 official clean 模式，结果可用于最终标注/质检写回：只复用语言级 Docker 镜像，不挂依赖缓存 volume，每题仍使用干净 repo copy 和一次性容器。该脚本会先执行 Docker preflight；macOS 上 Docker Desktop 已安装但 daemon/socket 未就绪时，会自动 `open -a Docker` 并等待最多 180 秒。Dockerfile 选择会先解析 `image_key` 中的 `<lang>_general` 后缀，再用 `problem_statement` 和 `test_script` 的语言/命令线索校验；若题面/脚本证据与 `language` 字段一致且共同反驳 `image_key`，必须覆盖错误的 `image_key` 并记录 `image_key_override`，否则在 `image_key` 缺失时推断，最后才参考 `language` 字段；随后从 `/Users/bill/pro/codeGen/dockerfiles` 选择 `Dockerfile.python` / `Dockerfile.go` / `Dockerfile.java` / `Dockerfile.js` / `Dockerfile.ts` / `Dockerfile.c` / `Dockerfile.cpp` / `Dockerfile.rust`，按语言+Dockerfile hash 构建或复用本地审核镜像，例如 `codegen-qc-python:<hash>`，不要把 `instance_id` 放入镜像名。若内部 `hub.byted.org/envagent` 基础镜像无法解析/拉取，脚本会生成公开基础镜像版临时 Dockerfile 重试；在容器运行 `test_script` 前，脚本会根据 `requirements.txt`、`pyproject.toml`、`setup.py`、`package.json`、lockfile、`go.mod`、`pom.xml`、Gradle 文件、`Cargo.toml` 等常见依赖声明自动 best-effort 拉取安装项目依赖，日志记录在 `docker_run.md` / `dependency_auto_install`，但自动补装本身不作为样本缺陷；若 Python `requirements.txt` 整体安装失败，准备脚本会逐条 fallback 安装可安装的依赖，不能因为一个旧包构建失败导致已可安装的包缺失而误判脚本。本地运行只能作为 Docker 基础设施失败后的补充排查，不能替代 Docker 验证，也不能把“本地跑过”写成样本已在 Docker 中验证。Docker 基础设施失败、本地补跑、静态复核三类证据必须分开记录，避免污染附件和原仓库。脚本会额外生成 `review_brief.md` / `review_brief.json`，标注时先读这个短摘要，再按需打开原附件或长日志，避免无谓消耗 token。\n8. 语言级镜像缓存、跨进程 build lock 和 `prewarm_qc_images.py` 是安全提速，不改变最终运行环境；`review_brief.md` / `docker_run.md` / `review_brief.json` 必须记录实际 image、Dockerfile、Dockerfile hash、语言来源、fallback 状态、`cache_mode=official`、`cache_volumes_enabled=false`。\n9. 依赖缓存 volume 只能作为显式 fast 模式 opt-in，用 `--mode fast` 或 `--docker-cache-volumes` 开启，只用于提前跑、粗筛和排队；fast 结果必须记录 `cache_mode=fast`、`cache_volumes_enabled=true`、`mounted_cache_volumes=[...]`，且不能单独支撑环境、依赖、脚本可运行性或 Docker 备注等最终结论。最终写回前必须有 official clean 证据。\n10. 并发可以跑，但每个 instance 必须使用独立目录 `workspaces/<instance_id>/_qc_docker_repo`、`workspaces/<instance_id>/_qc_docker_logs`、独立 `test_files_extracted` 和 `test_script` 临时文件，不共享源码/测试/构建产物目录，不固定容器名，不默认共享 host 端口。推荐 fetch/static 6-10，Docker official clean 默认 2-3、资源足够可 5，Feishu writeback 1。\n11. official clean 并发运行中出现失败、超时、自动依赖安装后的网络/DNS/registry 错误、daemon 异常、资源不足、OOM、磁盘 IO 或端口冲突等疑似瞬时/并发环境现象时，不得直接写成样本环境问题；必须标记 `needs_serial_clean_recheck=true` 并单题串行 official clean 重跑。普通依赖版本冲突、缺系统库、ModuleNotFoundError 等在单题 official clean 中稳定复现时，只作为环境排查上下文，不得作为修订后 1 分原因；测试脚本路径错误、选错测试、漏跑测试或退出码处理错误应按真实根因进入 `script_issues`。不要仅因成功构建日志里出现 `pip install` / `npm install` 等字样误触发串行复核。最终写回前如果仍有 `needs_serial_clean_recheck=true`，必须阻止写回或明确提示需要复核。\n\n## 审核 SOP\n\n### 1. 完整性\n\n确认 `instance_id`、`problem_statement`、`test_files`、`test_script` 可读；`rollout_result_json` 如存在则下载并解析。这里的数据完整性要先确认，但 Step 1 的一致性硬停止只看 `problem_statement` 与 `test_files` 是否完全不匹配：\n\n- 运行 `feishu_preflight.py <instance_id>`，确认目标行存在，并记录 `record_id`、`repo_url`、`language`、`image_key` 和附件摘要。\n- 运行 `fetch_instance.py <instance_id>`，确认 `manifest.json`、`record.raw.json`、`problem_statement`、`test_files`、`test_script`、`rollout_result_json` 下载成功，文件可读且非空。\n- 确认 `test_files.zip` 能解压，解压后的文件名和目录看起来属于当前 repo/任务，不是空包或串样本。\n- 对 `repo_url` 执行 `git ls-remote` 或浅克隆，尽量确认 GitHub 仓库真实可访问；如已有本地 `repo/`，核对 remote 和当前样本一致。仓库仅辅助理解需求、依赖和命名，不用仓库代码是否匹配来判错。\n- 解析 `rollout_result_json`，确认 JSON 合法，且内部 `instance_id` 与当前 `instance_id` 一致。\n- 核对 `language` 与 `image_key` 是否一致，例如 `language=go` 应能对应 `go_general` 镜像线索；不一致时只作为 Dockerfile/环境选择线索，不自动写成题测错误。若题面/脚本证据和 `language` 一致但与 `image_key` 冲突，Dockerfile 必须按题面/脚本证据选择。\n- 核对 `problem_statement` 与 `test_files` 的核心目标、接口、输入输出、FR/断言是否属于同一任务。只有完全不匹配时，才按 Step 1 停止并把原因写入 `备注`。\n- 静态读取 `test_script`，若发现它会修改源码或测试文件，例如 `sed -i`、`perl -pi`、`python -c` 改文件、`go mod edit`、`npm pkg set`、覆盖/删除 repo 文件、改 module/import、改测试断言、跳过失败或吞退出码，记录为后续 `test_script_review.script_issues`，不要因脚本与仓库冲突而提前停止。\n- 快速查看题面基础依赖、模块名、导入路径、结构体/函数名与 repo 当前实际代码是否有差异时，只把它当作理解需求和环境的参考；GitHub 代码与需求文档、测试脚本不匹配，不算错误，不需要写进 `备注`。\n\nStep 1 停止处理：只有 `problem_statement` 与 `test_files` 完全不匹配时，只更新表格 `备注` 字段写明具体原因并停止任务。备注内容只保留原因本身，不添加固定前缀。字段缺失、附件打不开、zip 损坏、rollout JSON 不能解析等是数据阻断，按具体阻断处理；不要把 GitHub 代码与题面/脚本不匹配写成错误，也不要修改任何源字段。\n\n### 2. 仓库理解\n\n阅读 repo 的 README、目录结构、依赖文件和任务涉及模块。可以让 agent 先生成 `research.md`，但最终判断必须人工复核关键文件。目标是理解项目上下文、依赖和命名习惯；原仓库不是标准答案，仓库代码与需求文档或测试脚本不匹配时，不算标注错误，不写入 `备注`，也不能作为新需求文档二次评分未达 5 分的理由。\n\n### 3. 需求检查\n\n阅读 `problem_statement`，提取：\n- 任务目标\n- 必须实现的文件、类、函数、CLI、API 或配置\n- 输入输出和边界条件\n- 依赖、环境、数据文件、禁止事项\n- FR 编号、文件结构表、验收说明\n\n需求必须像真实 PRD/功能需求，而不是把 UT 输入输出或测试文件翻译一遍。需求不清、接口缺失、环境依赖没讲清，记录到 `problem_statement_review.missing_requirements`，必要时在 `问题描述` 摘要说明；如果泄漏答案、硬指向原实现、无法从零实现，记录到 `over_specified_or_leaky_details` 并按严重程度降分。\n\n需求问题统一写在 meta 的 `problem_statement_review` 大类里：若测试暴露的问题源自 `problem_statement` 本身，例如误导模型使用错误语言/版本/依赖、遗漏必要环境前提、或通过修改需求即可让题目可用，标 `problem_statement_unclear=true`，并把具体 FR 证据写入 `missing_requirements`、`over_specified_or_leaky_details` 或 `untestable_requirements`。不要把这类问题只写进 `test_script_review` 或 `rollout_audit`。如果同一问题也写入了 `test_script_review.test_environment_issues`，例如需求文档中的 Python/Node/Go/JDK/依赖版本错误导致运行失败，…1025 tokens truncated…_review.alignment_issues`，并设置 `problem_and_tests_match=false`、`tests_require_unstated_behavior=true` 或 `tests_too_brittle=true`；`missing_requirements` 只在题面确实少写测试依赖信息时补，不要把这种二选一冲突降格成“需求可补充”。\n- 脚本漏跑、吞退出码、合并 stdout/stderr 后只看关键词、或 mock 明知无法验证需求，归脚本/测试验证问题，写 `script_issues`；若导致 FR 实际未验证，也同步写 `alignment_issues`。\n- 运行工具链、依赖安装、基础镜像、系统组件等执行证据写 `test_environment_issues`；如果根因是题面版本/依赖/运行方式写错，也要在 `problem_statement_review` 写主因，并同步写入 `missing_requirements`。真正基础设施阻断写入 meta，并在 `备注` / `问题描述` 简短摘要。普通缺依赖、依赖版本与 `test_files` 冲突或其他可由模型按需求文档配置解决的环境问题，不作为修订后低分或 `修改后仍然无法5分原因`。\n- 不要因为 test files 与原仓库文件一致就自动写 `over_specified_or_leaky_details`。该字段只写题面泄漏答案、硬指定实现、或把测试脚本/评测细节塞进题面的情况；测试附件异常优先看 `ut_transfer_problem`、`alignment_issues` 或 `script_issues`。\n- 典型抽检反例：参数错误未测、退出码未查；分隔符/大小写/空列表/顺序等边界漏测；mock 注释承认无法验证 timeout body-read；C 项目题面很大但只跑部分 bundled harness。这些都不是 `missing_requirements`，应先落到 `alignment_issues`。\n\n新增防漏复核（标注阶段必须做）：\n- 把每个 FR 拆成原子子项，不允许用一个 happy path 代表整个 FR。参数数量、退出码、大小写、空列表、顺序、分隔符、终止符、格式符、哨兵字段、状态读写、localStorage/缓存/队列状态等都要逐项核对。\n- 对题面列出的枚举集合做 diff：tag、事件名、路由、CLI 参数、格式符、状态码、错误码、配置项、公开结构体字段、supported IDs 等。题面有而测试没断言是弱覆盖，测试有而题面没写是测试超纲或题面缺失。\n- 对公开 API 和命名集合做 diff：方法名、构造函数、参数数量/顺序、回调接口、返回类型、环境变量、配置 key、命令行参数等。测试实际使用的名字和题面声明不兼容时，必须写出 FR、需求位置、测试文件/测试函数和冲突项。\n- 做“边界语义反查”：凡是题面出现 `MUST NOT`、`tolerate`、`empty`、`nil`、`default`、`invalid`、`non-zero exit`、`case-insensitive` 等词，必须把测试实际期望翻译成人话，例如 `expect error` / `expect no error`、`exit 0` / `non-zero exit`，再和 FR 对齐；不能只看测试名或是否存在同名用例。\n- 源码正则、字段存在、实例类型、字符串包含、mock 请求能跑，不等于行为验证。若测试没有执行到题面承诺的真实行为路径，默认按 `tests_too_weak` 候选处理。\n- 测试注释也是证据。若注释承认 mock/单测无法验证 timeout、body-read、integration、跨 realm、并发/时序等关键行为，要写入 `alignment_issues` 或 `script_issues`，不能只放备注。\n\n### 5. 测试脚本检查\n\n必须自己把 Docker 跑起来，在容器里把项目和测试脚本跑一遍；不能只做本地运行或静态阅读。默认通过 `codegen_qc_prepare.py <instance_id>` 完成 Docker 临时副本、测试文件 overlay、自动依赖安装、脚本执行和日志采集；脚本会自动启动 Docker Desktop 并等待 daemon 就绪。Dockerfile 选择先解析 `image_key` 的 `<lang>_general` 后缀，随后用 `problem_statement` 和 `test_script` 校验该语言是否合理；如果题面/脚本证据与 `language` 字段一致并共同反驳 `image_key`，按题面/脚本证据覆盖；如果 `image_key` 缺失或无法解析，再用题面/脚本线索推断，最后才用 `language` 字段兜底。若 Dockerfile 的 `FROM hub.byted.org/envagent/...` 无法解析/拉取，必须先用脚本生成的公开基础镜像 fallback 重试，优先保证 Docker 能运行项目。只有 Docker preflight 失败、所选语言 Dockerfile 缺失、公开 fallback 后仍镜像构建失败或用户明确要求不启动 Docker 时，才把 Docker 限制作为候选环境证据；如果镜像已构建且容器已进入 `test_script`，首次缺少常规项目依赖应由准备脚本自动拉取安装，不要写成报告问题。如果 Docker 构建、镜像或容器运行基础设施失败，可以再尝试用干净本地环境运行，但本地结果只能用于定位原因，不能替代 Docker 结论。然后结合实际运行结果阅读 `test_script`，确认：\n- 运行命令是否指向指定 `test_files`，没有误跑全仓库或错文件。\n- 依赖安装、环境变量、`PYTHONPATH`、Node/Go/Java/C/C++ 编译路径是否完整。\n- 失败是否会返回非零退出码。\n- 脚本是否绕过 `package.json`、复制测试文件到错误目录、依赖私有网络或系统资源。\n- 脚本、题目和测试文件的依赖版本是否冲突；这类冲突只作为环境配置上下文，默认模型会按需求文档装好依赖，不得单独作为修订后 1 分原因。\n- 如果 `problem_statement` 没说明运行环境，`test_script` 是否补足依赖、路径、环境变量、系统组件和前置数据。\n- 脚本是否实际运行全部提供的 `test_files`。若脚本选择器、路径、复制逻辑或命令只运行其中一部分，导致某些测试文件永远不执行，或因此测试运行失败/无法验证完整测试集合，属于测试异常；修订后仍无法 5 时 `修改后的匹配度（1-5分）` 不得低于原始分数，并在 `修改后仍然无法5分原因` 明确写“测试异常：测试脚本未运行全部 test_files”及漏跑证据。\n\n环境归因先按需求配置环境：若按题面和仓库依赖能跑通，或准备脚本自动安装依赖后能跑通，则环境没问题，不要把首次缺包写进报告或 meta 缺陷。若自动安装后仍因私有源、不可获得依赖、系统组件、版本冲突或题面误导的运行方式失败，可以把具体证据写入 meta JSON 的 `test_script_review.test_environment_issues` 或 `script_issues` 作为排查上下文；如果修改 `problem_statement` 即可解决，则归为需求问题并写入 `problem_statement_review`。但缺少依赖、依赖版本与 `test_files` 冲突或其他环境问题默认都按“模型应按需求文档配置好环境”处理，不作为修订后低分或 `修改后仍然无法5分原因`。模型完成实现后应自行安装项目依赖；若需求清楚而模型没有安装，通常是模型实现/轨迹问题。使用新需求文档重新打分时，不要再把原 GitHub 仓库代码问题作为扣分原因。\n\n脚本本身不可运行、路径错、文件名错、只做关键词检查、误跑测试、依赖私有网络/镜像、环境不稳定时，先在 meta 的 `test_script_review.script_issues` / `missing_test_info` / `test_environment_issues` 中标记。真正让测试进不去的基础设施阻断，例如 Docker daemon 不可用、语言 Dockerfile 缺失、公开 fallback 后仍构建失败、容器存储/平台/设备不可用，要写入 meta 并在 `备注` / `问题描述` 摘要；容器已启动并执行自动依赖安装与 `test_script` 后，不要继续写“本机 Docker 未运行”，也不要把已被自动安装解决的缺包写成问题。若自动安装后仍失败，可记录容器内具体 stdout/stderr、私有依赖、版本冲突、测试路径、构建步骤或服务前置问题；其中普通缺依赖/依赖冲突只作环境上下文，不作修订后 1 分证据。Docker 失败后本地环境能跑通时，要明确写出 Docker 基础设施失败原因和本地验证结果，并把本地结果标成补充证据；没有 Docker 容器运行证据时，不得把样本判成“Docker 环境已验证”。\n\n测试文件缺失的判定要收窄到测试集合自身不可用：`test_files` 解压后测试目录里都是实现源文件、没有测试文件或任何可执行测试行为；或 `test_script` 为了测试某功能需要关键辅助文件/fixture/helper，但该文件既不在 `test_files` 中，也没有在需求文档中说明，且无法推断其代码逻辑、不能通过补需求文档让模型实现。以上都属于无法靠需求修订解决的测试异常；修订后评分不得低于原始分数，并在 `修改后仍然无法5分原因` 写清缺失文件或无测试行为的证据。不要把普通依赖包、可安装工具链、系统库或版本差异当成测试文件缺失。\n\n### 6. Rollout 审核\n\n解析 `rollout_result_json` 中的 history、score、eval_stdout、eval_stderr、finish_reason。要搜索模型轨迹、`eval_stderr`、依赖安装日志、运行命令和最后失败栈；结合需求判断失败是模型没做、题面误导、脚本缺陷，还是基础环境/依赖安装失败。重点：\n- `score==1` 也要看是否有复制原仓库、硬编码测试、修改测试、绕过 verifier、命中 canary 等风险。\n- `score==0` 要区分是模型没做对、题测不匹配、脚本问题、环境/沙盒问题，还是平台异常。\n- 如果发现作弊或明显违规，`final_label=REJECT`，`是否可用=❌不可用`，并在 `rollout_audit.cheating_or_copying_evidence` 和 `问题描述` / meta 写证据。\n- 轨迹很长或可疑时，可以用两个以上模型辅助筛查；但不能直接复制模型结论，必须回到具体步骤、日志或文件片段人工确认。\n- 没有轨迹问题时 meta 相关数组填 `[]`，不要编造。\n\n## 需求文档修订流程\n\n只要原始第一次质检不是 `5` 分，就必须完整执行修订流程，不能只停留在第一轮结论。也就是说，`2/3/4/1` 都必须生成并上传同一轮的 `修改后的需求文档` 和 `diff_report`，写入 `修改后的匹配度（1-5分）`；如果修订后仍不是 `5`，还必须继续写 `修改后仍然无法5分原因`，把流程走完整，不能漏任何一步。修订后的需求文档应尽量吸收可修复的需求、环境、依赖、版本和运行方式问题，使重评匹配度达到 5 分。无论根因是需求文档问题、测试附件问题、测试脚本问题，还是预判“修改需求也无法到 5”，都必须跑完整修订流程；不得因为已知不能到 5 分就跳过上传新文档、`diff_report`、修改后评分和原因。\n\n1. 先产出当前问题点 meta JSON，路径通常是 `/Users/bill/pro/codeGen/workspaces/<instance_id>/<instance_id>_meta.json`。如果 Docker 启动阶段因系统组件、版本、基础镜像或自动依赖安装后仍不可恢复的依赖问题失败，也可以把具体环境证据写进这个 meta JSON，帮助修订需求时减少环境问题干扰；已被自动安装解决的普通缺包不要写入问题点。\n2. 调用：\n   ```bash\n   python3 /Users/bill/pro/codeGen/script/codegen_revise_problem_statement.py <instance_id>\n   ```\n   该脚本会把用户指定的 XML prompt 原封不动发送给 Codex 5.5 high，只替换五个 placeholder：`folderName` 为整个题目工作区，`jsonFile` 为 meta JSON 路径，`testFile` 为 `test_files` 附件路径，`testScript` 为 `test_script` 附件路径，`requirementsDoc` 为 `problem_statement` 附件路径。不要手改 prompt 里的其他字段。\n3. Codex 修订完成后必须核对两个产物：被修改后的需求文档，以及工作区内的 `diff_report.md`。只要原始第一次质检不是 `5` 分，这两个产物都属于必交件，`diff_report.md` 要按 FR 点记录修改明细和跳过项，不能省略。\n4. 用新需求文档重新做一次题测对齐和评分。重新评分时只判断新需求文档、`test_files`、`test_script` 是否匹配；GitHub 原仓库代码仍只是辅助理解，不得作为“修改后仍然无法 5 分”的原因。此时分数理应达到 5；不得把已经被新需求文档修复的旧缺口继续作为扣分原因。\n5. 如果新需求文档重评仍不是 5，不能直接停止在当前分数。先把剩余扣分点重新拆到 meta JSON：能通过需求文档修复的内容必须写回 `problem_statement_review.missing_requirements` 或相关需求字段；环境不匹配、缺依赖、依赖版本与 `test_files` 冲突、版本/运行方式说明不清时，允许并且应该修改作为修订输入的需求文档内容中的环境要求、依赖列表、版本约束、安装命令或运行前置条件，最终只作为 `修改后的需求文档` 新附件上传，不覆盖源字段，也不能把这些问题当作“修改后仍然无法 5 分原因”。\n6. 调整 meta JSON 后，必须再次调用 `codegen_revise_problem_statement.py <instance_id>`，用更新后的 meta JSON 重新生成/调整需求文档和 `diff_report.md`，然后按新文档重新做题测对齐和评分；如环境/依赖说明已变更，能进入 official clean 的情况下还要重新运行 `test_script` 或复用准备脚本重跑验证，确认新需求下是否可达到 5 分。不得把已由二次需求文档修复的旧问题继续作为扣分原因。\n7. 只有在二次调整后仍确认“即使模型 100% 按修改后的需求文档实现仓库代码、并按文档配置好环境，也必然无法通过测试”时，才进入结构性必败分支。典型证据包括测试文件缺失/损坏、测试目录全是实现源文件且没有任何测试行为、测试逻辑内部冲突、断言互相矛盾、脚本必然漏跑/误跑目标测试、脚本不运行全部提供的 `test_files` 导致失败或无法验证完整测试集合、测试依赖的关键文件/fixture/helper 在样本中不可获得且无法通过需求说明补齐。此时 `修改后的匹配度（1-5分）` 不得低于原始分数，并在 `修改后仍然无法5分原因` 写明“测试异常”以及为什么必然无法通过测试；必要时 `备注` 只补一句特殊原因摘要。\n8. 写回时上传最终版本的新需求文档到 `修改后的需求文档` 字段，上传同一轮生成的 `diff_report.md` 到 `diff_report` 字段，并把最终新文档重评分数写到 `修改后的匹配度（1-5分）` 字段。只要原始第一次质检不是 `5` 分，这三项都是必须写回的；如果最终新文档重新评分不是 `5`，必须把没给 `5` 分的具体原因写到 `修改后仍然无法5分原因` 字段，不能因为已经判断样本结构性不佳就跳过该字段。不要因为新文档重评变成 5 分就把 `是否可用` 改成 `✅可用`；该字段只保留原始第一次评分对应的值。\n\n带修订附件的写回命令示例：\n\n```bash\npython3 /Users/bill/pro/codeGen/script/codegen_qc_writeback.py <instance_id> \\\n  --revised-problem-statement /Users/bill/pro/codeGen/workspaces/<instance_id>/attachments/problem_statement/<file>.md \\\n  --diff-report /Users/bill/pro/codeGen/workspaces/<instance_id>/diff_report.md\n```\n\n## 评分和标签\n\n`5`：题目和测试高度匹配；需求背景、接口、输入输出、边界、依赖清楚；测试覆盖核心功能和关键异常路径；脚本正确；没有隐藏行为。若测试未完全覆盖题目需求，或测试了题目未说明内容，不能给 5。\n\n`4`：基本完备；核心信息齐全；测试和题目匹配，没有测试题目未说明行为；可能缺少少量边界、环境说明或非核心约束；测试未覆盖全部题目需求时可给 4。\n\n`3`：部分完备，需要修改；能看出需求，但存在明显缺口，或测试包含少量题目未说明行为，人工补充后才适合训练。\n\n`2`：不够完备；题目和测试弱匹配，关键接口、依赖、输入输出、边界缺失较多，模型需要靠猜或读测试才能完成。\n\n`1`：严重不完备；题目和测试明显不匹配、测试不是有效测试、脚本无法可靠运行，或任务需要重写/废弃。若需求明确声明的公开 API、函数签名、回调形态、配置 key 或环境变量与测试实际使用不兼容，属于需求和测试文件冲突，原始评分判 1。修订后重评时，即使存在测试目录没有测试行为、缺关键辅助测试文件、测试脚本不运行全部 `test_files` 导致失败或无法验证完整集合等测试异常，也不得把 `修改后的匹配度（1-5分）` 打到低于原始分数。\n\n最终标签硬对应：\n- `5` -> `✅可用` / `ACCEPT`：需求清晰，测试严谨且完全匹配，脚本/环境无明显问题，rollout 无作弊。\n- `2`、`3`、`4` -> `⚠️需修改` / `NEEDS_REVISION`：样本有价值，但需求、测试或脚本需要补充或修正。\n- `1` -> `❌不可用` / `REJECT`：严重不匹配、测试无效、脚本/沙盒不可可靠验证、无法从零实现、任务性质偏离或存在作弊。\n\n## 输出字段写法\n\n- `问题描述`：概括该样本的主要问题。可用样本写 `无明显问题` 或一句核心风险；不可用样本要说明题目不清、测试不匹配、测试异常、轨迹异常或沙盒基础设施问题，不要把普通依赖缺失/依赖冲突写成不可用主因。\n- `备注`：没有需要说明的内容时必须留空，不要写 `无`；若 Step 1 发现 `problem_statement` 与 `test_files` 完全不匹配，只写具体原因并停止任务；若 Docker daemon、镜像或容器基础设施无法构建/启动/进入 `test_script`，写 Docker 基础设施摘要。容器内普通项目依赖缺失由准备脚本自动安装，已解决的不写备注；自动安装后仍失败的私有依赖、系统组件、脚本或题测问题按实际归因写入 meta/问题描述，但普通缺依赖/依赖冲突不作修订后 1 分证据。修订后重评分数仍不是 5 时，可写一句特殊原因摘要，详细原因仍写 `修改后仍然无法5分原因`。GitHub 代码与题面或脚本不匹配不写备注。不要给备注加固定前缀。\n- `质检备注`：当前表可能没有列写权限，默认不要写入 payload；短句结论放在 `问题描述`，详细列表写入 meta。只有脚本/预检确认该列可写或用户明确要求时才写。\n- `修改后的需求文档` / `diff_report`：执行需求文档修订流程后必须上传；必须和同次修订产物对应。\n- `修改后的匹配度（1-5分）`：执行需求文档修订流程后必填。新文档已经按测试修订后理应为 5；第一次修订后若不是 5，必须先二次调整 meta JSON，把可修复的环境、依赖、依赖冲突、版本、安装命令、运行方式或测试上下文写进修改后的需求文档，再重新生成、重评并按需重跑测试；该分数不得低于原始 `完备性评分（1-5分）`，也不得用它改写 `是否可用`。\n- `修改后仍然无法5分原因`：最终新需求文档重新评分仍低于 5 时必填；若即使完美实现并配置好环境也必然无法通过测试，`修改后的匹配度（1-5分）` 不得低于原始分数，并在此说明“测试异常”及测试逻辑冲突、测试目录无测试行为、关键测试辅助文件缺失、脚本未运行全部 `test_files` 等证据。环境不匹配、缺依赖或依赖版本与 `test_files` 冲突应默认视为可配置环境问题，优先写进修订后的需求文档并二次重评；能给 5 时留空。\n- 所有问题描述都要具体到文件、测试名、FR、脚本行或 rollout 证据，避免只写“测试不匹配”“接口访问失败”这种单句标签。\n\n## JSON 质量硬门槛\n\n当前 code_GEN 项目整体试标质量不佳，主要问题集中在最终 `汇总字段（meta json）` 的 JSON 数据格式。以后每条标注都必须把 JSON 格式当作硬质检项，不允许只人工看一眼就上传。\n"}}
